# Systemd Hermes Daemon Template

## Overview

Use systemd user services to manage Hermes Python daemons reliably. This replaces wrapper scripts and nohup with proper process supervision, automatic restarts, and journald logging.

## Unit File Template

Save as `~/.config/systemd/user/hermes-<name>.service`:

```ini
[Unit]
Description=Hermes %i Daemon
After=network-online.target
Wants=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=%i
# If running as yourself, use:
# User=1000
# Group=1000

WorkingDirectory=/opt/data/home/.hermes
EnvironmentFile=/opt/data/.env

# Main daemon start
ExecStart=/usr/bin/python3 -u /opt/data/home/.hermes/scripts/%i.py

# Optional: pre/post hooks
# ExecStartPre=/opt/data/home/.hermes/scripts/healthcheck-%i.sh
# ExecStopPost=/opt/data/home/.hermes/scripts/cleanup-%i.sh

# Logging to both journald and file
StandardOutput=journal
StandardError=journal

# Capture logs to file too (optional)
# StandardOutput=append:/opt/data/home/.hermes/logs/%i_%Y%m%d.log
# StandardError=append:/opt/data/home/.hermes/logs/%i_%Y%m%d.log

# Restart policy
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=30
StartLimitIntervalSec=300
StartLimitBurst=3

# Resource limits (tune per script)
# MemoryLimit=500M
# CPUQuota=50%

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target
```

## Per-Script Customization

For `x_link_poller_v2.py` → unit name: `hermes-x-link-poller.service`

```bash
# Template the unit file
cat > ~/.config/systemd/user/hermes-x-link-poller.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Hermes X Link Poller v2
After=network-online.target
Wants=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=1000
WorkingDirectory=/opt/data/home/.hermes
EnvironmentFile=/opt/data/.env
ExecStart=/usr/bin/python3 -u /opt/data/home/.hermes/scripts/x_link_poller_v2.py
StandardOutput=journal
StandardError=journal
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=10

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target
EOF
```

## Enabling & Managing

```bash
# Reload systemd user manager
systemctl --user daemon-reload

# Enable at login (creates symlink)
systemctl --user enable hermes-x-link-poller.service

# Start immediately
systemctl --user start hermes-x-link-poller.service

# Check status
systemctl --user status hermes-x-link-poller.service
# Green "active (running)" = good

# View logs (journald)
journalctl --user -u hermes-x-link-poller.service -f

# Stop
systemctl --user stop hermes-x-link-poller.service

# Disable autostart
systemctl --user disable hermes-x-link-poller.service

# Restart
systemctl --user restart hermes-x-link-poller.service
```

## User vs System Services

- **User services** (`--user`): Run in your user session, access XDG dirs, easier for dev
- **System services** (`/etc/systemd/system/`): Run as root or dedicated user, start at boot before login

For Hermes daemons, use **user services** unless you need boot-early availability without login.

## Common Gotchas

| Problem | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| `Failed to connect to bus: No such file or directory` | `export XDG_RUNTIME_DIR=/run/user/$(id -u)` |
| `Unit hermes-xxx.service not found` | Run `systemctl --user daemon-reload` after editing |
| `Access denied` on vault/log paths | Ensure `User=` has write permission to those paths |
| Environment variables not loaded | Ensure `EnvironmentFile=/opt/data/.env` exists and is readable |
| Service dies immediately | Check `journalctl --user -u hermes-xxx.service -n 50` for stderr |

## Migration: Wrapper → systemd

**Before** (wrapper with deadlock):
```bash
# /opt/data/home/.hermes/scripts/start-x-poller.sh
while true; do
  python3 x_link_poller_v2.py | tee -a log
  sleep 120
done
```

**After** (systemd, no wrapper):
```bash
# 1. Remove wrapper script or disable it
# 2. Install unit file as shown above
systemctl --user enable --now hermes-x-link-poller.service
```

The Python script's internal `while True` + `time.sleep(300)` is now managed by systemd's `Restart=on-failure`.

## Verification

```bash
# Should show exactly one process chain:
#   systemd → python3 → script internals
ps -eo pid,ppid,stat,cmd | grep hermes | grep -v grep

# No orphan accumulation
# No wrapper process lingering
# Journald shows cyclical "Sleeping 300s" messages
```

## Notes

- Systemd tracks process via cgroup, so even if Python respawns subprocesses, they're contained
- Logs go to `journalctl --user` by default; can also tee to file if needed
- `RestartSec=10` = 10s backoff between restarts if script crashes
- `StartLimitBurst=3` = fail after 3 restarts in 300s, prevents crash loops
